  "text": "Pharmacologically, PAF is one of the most potent inducers of vascular permeability [CITATION_1] reported in the literature. Consequently, induction of PAF release by the presence of the blastocyst, together with the synergistic vasoactive effects of PAF [CITATION_2] and prostaglandins , could play an important physiological role in the blastocystinduced vascular permeability in the stroma of the rabbit uterus commencing at 6 days of preg¬ nancy and observable by Day 6-5 of pregnancy (Hoos & Hoffman, 1980) . Such an interpretation is strengthened by the low levels of PAF in the myometrium, minimal PAF changes in myometrium with increased progesterone concentrations, and lack of differences in myometrial PAF between pregnant and pseudopregnant animals (Table 4 ). This suggests that the observed endometrial changes are not artefactual.",
